<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>all works of art are equally important, nomatter who creates them, and nomatter what motivation the artist actually has to create them.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
No, they are not. Some art is better than other art, and some art is more important than other art. Different mediums may all be valid, but there are varying degrees of quality between each piece of art. A young child's stick figures on lined paper is not on par with Michelangelo's Sistine Chapel paintings, for example. It may be valid, hell, it may even have some meaning, but it is NOT as good, and it is certainly not as important as something that has actually survived hundreds of years and which has influenced other artists for just as long.<br>
<br>
I agree that in some cases, art is put down unfairly, and is judged solely on the medium, instead of the work itself, but to claim that ALL art is equally as good and equally as important is ridiculous. <p><html>
