<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>TECHNICAL EXPERTISE ITSELF ADEQUATE TO PRODUCE AN EMOTIONAL IMPACT.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Saying all art is valid is hard to refute. At some point, to some person, so long as someone considers it art (even the creator), it is valid. However, that all works are equally important seems wonky.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;I am become Death, the shatterer of worlds.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
How are you measuring a work's importance? How it affects lives, inspires, or that it just exists? According to your and Mr. Hubbard's definition, an atomic explosion is a work of art. The technical expertise needed to create the explosion is immense. No one can deny that an emotional response accompanies viewing the frightful image of a mushroom cloud. Did Dr. J. Robert Oppenheimer consider himself an artist? Probably not. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=souridaijin@polykarbonbbs>Souridaijin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/7/03 6:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12617.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: a debate on art and validity</span><hr size=1> Ah...the eternal debate on the definition of art. Here's my two cents. Think about this for a sec. To me it seems like humans are the only living creatures that create &quot;art&quot; conciously. Dogs, cats, birds, and ants, etc, etc, do not (at least not to my knowledge). It also seems obvious to me that although animals do have feelings, human emotions are much more sophisticated. These two observations do not connect directly into each other, but my point is this: I think animals can't make art because they don't have enough emotions in themselves to be inpired to make art. I think emotion and the artist's desire to express it in some way (ie: art) is a huge part of the definition of art. To me, the more emotion that goes into the art, the more meaning it has, and the more emotions it provokes the more important it is. What do you think about my theory?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://china.kyodo.co.jp/2002/home/img/pix20021106-" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END-->[/img] <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=emmapeel1601>emmapeel1601</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.geocities.com/garaigh/emma2.txt" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/7/03 8:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12617.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/garaigh/buddy2.txt height=127 width=107></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: a debate on art and validity</span><hr size=1> what an interesting topic. this could go on for quite a while. i must say that my views on &quot;art&quot; have been greatly influenced by Andrei Tarkovsky (a Russian film-maker of extreme genuis) and his book Sculpting in Time. it's quite fascinating and a bit of a different look at art since in this case the &quot;art&quot; is moving images, not paint or sculpture, etc. <br>
<br>
anyway, he has this to say about art. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>In any case it is perfectly clear that the goal for all art - unless of course it is aimed at the &quot;consumer&quot;, like a saleable commodity - is to explain to the artist himself and those around him what man lives for, what is the meaning of his existence. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is perhaps not a vastly different definition of art than what a lot of people discuss. But Tarkovsky then takes a very different tack by tying art directly to spirituality. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Art is born and takes hold wherever there is a timeless and insatiable longing for the spiritual, for the ideal: that longing which draws people to art. Modern art has taken a wrong turn in abandoning the search for the meaning of existence in order to affirm the value of the individual for its own sake. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And then...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The artist is always a servant, and is perpetually trying to pay for the gift that has been given to him as if by a miracle. Modern man, however, does not want to make any sacrifice, even though true affirmation of self can only be expressed in sacrifice.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
i'm sure there are plenty of people on this board and in the world who disagree with this perspective on art. but i found that it is very well-developed (in other words, the concept goes further and holds together much better than most i've read) and rather unique. so, when this topic popped up i figured &quot;why not share?&quot;<br>
<br>
i agree with pretty much everything Tarkovsky says, not because i threw my mind out the window and said &quot;oh, this looks like a good thing&quot; but because i believe he had great insight into the creative process and how and why it works (or doesn't.) it's all well and good to say that all art is valid but i really don't think that's true. if a piece of work doesn't produce some emotion in every person that sees it, then it's failed in its purpose to communicate. (i know this is a point many will disagree with but it's my personal opinion.) not everyone has to feel exactly the same thing when they look at a painting but if people (even if they are only a few) feel nothing, then something about the work is lacking. <br>
<br>
anyway, just my two cents. <br>
<br>
again, i highly recommend Tarkovsky's book, just as a different perspective on art and creativity. and the above statements are my opinion. i will defend them to the last but you don't have to swallow anything i say if you don't feel like it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
