<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>&quot;Damn you.. Just because you're a visually appealing little bastard, doesn't make you cool.  You're stupid, stupid, stupid!  I'll kill you, you poser, I'll definately make you die.&quot;</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=alucard1515>alucard1515</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator <img src=http://contest.polykarbon.com/badge1.gif></span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/8/03 1:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12617.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.undeadart.com/forum/alucard.gif width=100 height=94></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: a debate on art and validity</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You can compare Michelangelo to a child in that each may have put the same percent of work into their potential at the time. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Yes, and which of the two has more to put into it?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Just because the majority favors Michelangelo's medium, does not exactly prove that it is more meaningful than a stick figure of a child's imagination.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Very true, but what does that have to do with what I said? I said Michelangelo's work is more meaningful than a child's doodle, it has nothing to do with majority opinion or the medium in which they worked. His work is more meaningful, MUCH more meaningful. The child just plops down a stick figure with no thought to composition, form, or anatomy, and they certainly didn't have any deep intellectual meaning to their work, whereas Michelangelo's work is completely opposite. That I have to point this out at all is baffling to me.<br>
<br>
I don't live in a pretend world where everything is equal, because it's not. All art may be VALID, but it is most certainly not all equal.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>not everyone has to feel exactly the same thing when they look at a painting but if people (even if they are only a few) feel nothing, then something about the work is lacking.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
How could you possibly feel nothing? A blank wall elicits some kind of response out of people, a painting or other work of art is going to cause some kind of reaction, however small it may be. And if someone were able to actually produce a piece of art that could truly make you feel nothing, then they certainly would have achieved something. <p><html>
