<br>
actually, American Pie is entertainment, not art. or it's art in the same way that some comic strips are art. it's main purpose and function is not to be &quot;art&quot; but to entertain the masses. this is one reason why discussing films as art is difficult. they are generally geared more towards entertainment than anything else, at least in the U.S. <br>
<br>
Kurosawa didn't make films just to entertain people. he had a distinct creative vision behind every film and a very specific purpose in how he used the camera and film to achieve that vision. Dodes Kadan was his first color film. it flopped horribly and is still probably one of the the most depressing films you could ever watch. but the way he used color in the film borders on genuis. it's visually overwhelming and in complete contrast to the subject of the film. <br>
<br>
Alucard: as far as looking at something and feeling nothing, maybe i'm just weird but that's happened to me before. when i look at a blank wall i don't feel any emotional stirring other than boredom. and i've looked at paintings before and felt much the same. they didn't make me angry, confused, happy or sad, they simply left me feeling exactly the way i had when i walked into the gallery. <br>
<br>
now maybe i'm a freak and staring at a blue wall should make me feel different than staring at a white wall. but it doesn't. and it doesn't matter because no one said 'this blue wall is my artistic expression of the apathy of society in general.' it's just a blue wall. and if it were a giant canvas and someone had declared that it was a representation of the world's apathy? probably still wouldn't feel anything. i think a part of good art (whether it be abstract or more classical) is a certain level of complexity. the longer you look at something the more you should be able to see. <br>
<br>
so, that's my opinion unfolded a little. i used the wall (or giant canvas) as an arbitrary example. i've never seen a piece of artwork like that (although i'm sure there probably is one somewhere) and i'm not saying that it couldn't be done in such a way as to produce a response. just that this is the kind of thing that rarely stirs up any kind of emotion in me when i look at it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
