I didn't mean to disagree with you entirely, and I think this sentence sums up more of what I was thinking. I do think emotion is a part of art, I just don't think it's THE thing which makes or breaks the work. There is some work that can be admired for its technical proficiency, and emotion may be secondary. I think they should be judged differently, but I believe they are both art. Now, if a work is skillful and they FAILED at conveying the emotional response it was going for, it may not be great art, but it is still art.<br>
<br>
I like the idea here that creativity is what defines art more than I do emotion. Again, I believe that emotion is an important part of art, and makes a piece all the more meaningful, I just think that a work can still be admired for some aspects when it is lacking in others. <p><html>
